			<div class="content" id="post-content-4865847">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">[+]&nbsp;Open&nbsp;for&nbsp;crit</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>So, I was thinking that for the story, someone would find a journal of the creature in that dimension and based on the notes there he would discover that the creature was once a human but it was transformed into this anomaly after having found this lantern. He became the lantern bearer and was corrupted by it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>My personal feeling, and other reviewers may disagree, is that backstory like this is almost always the wrong approach to take in writing a SCP: the core issue (for me) is that the Foundation are writing this article, and so it's easier to get a reader invested if the Foundation actively take a protagonistic role in the story (i.e., they are the PoV telling the story, their decisions are the ones that should actually affect it). I don't necessarily dislike this as a start but imo you should take this and run with it and explore how the SCP feels know their the lantern bearer and how that's affected by the Foundation coming into view.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Uhhh, I forgot to mention it’s an oil lantern. It needs oil to stay lit, not wood. When it transforms you, you’ll become a tree full of oil. Then it will use that oil to fuel the lantern.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I'm a little torn on this because on the one hand, it still feels very complex but on the other, I guess it's kinda how rubber trees work.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I was thinking that it would add some nice background information, you know, make things more realistic, more believable.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Sure but you're trying to tell a cohesive short story here, adding in stuff that adds to the realism isn't necessarily a good idea if it doesn't add to the core of the story being told.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

